Answer RAG:
You can use the SharedPreferences in Android to store a long value representing the timestamp in milliseconds, which provides more precision than seconds. Here's a simple example:

SharedPreferences prefs = context.getSharedPreferences("MyPrefs", Context.MODE_PRIVATE);
SharedPreferences.Editor editor = prefs.edit();
editor.putLong("timestamp", System.currentTimeMillis());
editor.apply();
To retrieve the timestamp:

long timestamp = prefs.getLong("timestamp", 0);
This method avoids dividing by 1000 and retains millisecond precision.

